2020 CRAN Usage

2021-01-04

Overview

There follows a high-level report on CRAN package downloads. The source data for this report is the log data made available from the CRAN mirror service operated by RStudio.

The RStudio CRAN mirror is the default mirror used in the IDE. Naturally, the end user is free to change this and not all R users use the RStudio IDE. There are a great many alternate mirrors that an R user may choose to use as well as services like RStudios own Public Package Manager. As such, this report should be taken for what it is; a look at the traffic of a large CRAN mirror only and it may therefore not be representative of CRAN usage as a whole.

Methodology - counts have had duplicate values removed, for example, for the R version counts, we have no counted the same user twice for a particular day.

Total Downloads

In 2020 there were a total of 1,773,286,890 package downloads from the mirror.

The day with the highest number of package downloads, 7,343,716, was the 28th of April, which makes sense if we remember that R 4.0.0 was released on the 24th of April and its likely that users will have been installing packages after the upgrade.

Somewhat less explicably, the day with the lowest recorded number of package downloads, 813,895, was the 29th of February.

Other than those stand-outs, package downloads appear to follow a familliar seasonal pattern of dips in the Nerthern hemispheres Summer and Winter.

One interesting point that only become apparent when you plot downloads by day is that there are two clear clusters: one for weekdays and another for weekends. Whilst some of the weekend usage is likely to be work-related and some will be almost certainly be automated processes, I believe the strong weekend usage is indicative of the langauges popularity among maintainers of side-projects, learners and hobbyists.

Countries

Which countries are the heaviest users of R?

No surprises here. The chart is dominated by US based usage, which dwarfs usage in China which takes the number 2 spot.

Though we cant provide any evidence to suggest that this impacts the results, its worth remembering that all three of the planets biggest cloud providers are based in the US. As such they have a much larger presence in the US than in other territories and users in other countries will often use US regions for their cloud work in order to better serve US customers and access additional features not yet available in other regions.

By OS

Which operating systems do R users use?

Unsurprisingly, Windows takes the top spot. Linux (linux-gnu) puts in a strong showing, perhaps due to the number of production R systems in use. MacOS, also makes a strong showing (compared to its relative market share), likely due to its popularity as a development platform amongst R users. Taking the 4th and 5th spots respectively are linux-gnueabihf, which seems to be Linux for ARM based CPUs (which perhaps well see more of in the future) and linux-musl, which I believe could be Docker favourite Alpine Linux.
